The Beer and The Boycott


By Jonathan Tasini; Jonathan Tasini is a writer who specializes in labor issues.


Published: January 31, 1988









                    LAURENCE GOLD, THE A.F.L.-C.I.O.'S GEN-eral counsel, was up to his elbows in work one day in November 1984 when his phone rang.        

                    Calling was Robert H. Chanin, his counterpart at the National Education Association, the nation's largest labor union. Chanin was on a secret diplomatic mission. He told Gold that his union had been informally contacted by the Adolph Coors Company, which was seeking an end to the labor federation's seven-year boycott of Coors beer; the N.E.A. had just voted to support that ban. Chanin asked what it would take for the A.F.L.-C.I.O. to end the boycott, but, to his surprise, Gold didn't know.        

                    ''The A.F.L.-C.I.O. had been caught up in implementing the boycott, not ending it,'' Chanin says today.        

                    The fight against the Adolph Coors Company was one of the most bitter labor-management struggles of the last 30 years. After 1,472 brewery workers struck Coors in 1977, unions poured millions of dollars into a consumer boycott that effectively helped stunt the company's growth. Coors, ferociously antiunion, is the company political liberals love to hate, and the boycott became a cause celebre of the 1980's. Millions of people shunned Coors beer, just as sympathizers with migrant workers had banished grapes from their refrigerators in the 1960's and 1970's.        

                    Chanin's phone call, however, sparked three years of negotiations that last fall produced what many thought impossible - an agreement between the A.F.L.-C.I.O. and Coors that ended the boycott. It is a classic tale of labor-management relations - of two enemies slinging arrows at each other for years, until, battered by a changing economy, they needed each other badly enough to compromise.        

                    The agreement was largely the work of two men - Peter H. Coors, great-grandson of the company's founder and president of its brewery division since 1985, and Thomas R. Donahue, secretary-treasurer of the A.F.L.-C.I.O. - both of whom are trying to steer their organizations into the future.        

                    Under the guidance of Peter Coors and his older brother Jeffrey, president of the Adolph Coors Company, the brewery is attempting to double, within five years, its current 8 percent share of the American market, in order to contend in a troubled industry that everyone expects to be dominated by three or four breweries by the end of the century. ''Coors and the whole beer industry are under siege,'' says Frank Walters, research director for M. Shanken Communications, publishers of several alcoholic-beverage industry periodicals. ''The beer market will not grow because of the trend in moderation, the older population and the higher drinking age.''        

                    On the other side, Donahue has been trying to halt organized labor's slide toward irrelevancy. Since President Reagan's celebrated dismissal of striking air-traffic controllers in 1981, American companies have become more skillful and more determined in resisting or breaking unions. Union membership dropped from 22.4 million in 1980 to slightly less than 17 million in 1986. Organized labor has been in such desperate straits that the Coors settlement has been perceived as a victory - even though the workers at Coors are still without a union.        

                    AGAINST THE FOOTHILLS OF THE ROCKIES, IN the small town of Golden, Colo., the Adolph Coors Company sits on 3,300 acres. For Peter Coors, the brewery holds childhood memories. Born in 1946, Peter used to build forts out of towering stacks of empty bottles and cans. Once he turned 14, his summer vacations were spent working at the brewery. After receiving an industrial engineering degree from Cornell University and graduating from the University of Denver's business school, Peter came back to the company as a production trainee.        

                    Imbued with his business-school training, he poked around the company's financial systems and found a $350 million corporation in which department heads were oblivious to their budget, he says, and seven people ran the company's financial arm using the double-entry accounting method. Peter, young and cocky, revamped the procedures and worked hard on the public stock offering the company was forced into to pay off estate taxes for Adolph Coors Jr., Peter's grandfather. In 1975, he turned his attention to his true calling - sales and marketing.        

                    From the 1950's until Peter took charge, the brewery was run by Joseph and William Coors, Peter's father and uncle; by the early 70's, their product had an almost cultlike following. College kids, believing the beer brewed with Rocky Mountain spring water was special, raved about its taste. The problem for Coors wasn't selling beer; it was making enough beer to meet demand, which only reinforced Joe and Bill Coors's disdain for marketing.        

                    But times were changing. The clubby nature of the beer business had turned into a bruising battle. In the early 70's, the Miller Brewing Company, the nation's No. 2 brewer. embarked on a massive ad campaign. Anheuser-Busch, No. 1, countered with its own onslaught, spending tens of millions of dollars on television and radio spots as well as promotions. Initially, Coors was caught flat-footed; it was spending $3 million annually on advertising. ''We didn't have marketing research,'' Peter Coors says. ''Our sales people had been with us for 30 years.'' In 1979, at Peter's insistence, the company boosted its ad budget to $46 million.        







